, but turned against Imre Nagy \'s government after he denounced the Warsaw Pact . The party supported the \' Revolutionary Workers\'-Peasants\' Government of Hungary \' that took over the country, with Soviet support, on 4 November 1956. Gradually, however, the K\xc3\xa1d\xc3\xa1r regime instituted goulash Communism , a somewhat more humane way of governing than had prevailed under M\xc3\xa1ty\xc3\xa1s R\xc3\xa1kosi . Under K\xc3\xa1d\xc3\xa1r\'s mantra of "he who is not against us is with us," Hungarians generally had more freedom than their Eastern Bloc counterparts to go about their daily lives. The government also gave limited freedom to the workings of the market. While the MSzMP regime was not nearly as repressive as its Warsaw Pact counterparts, at bottom it was still authoritarian. It retained a monopoly of political power, and subjected the media to censorship that was fairly onerous by Western standards. The National Assembly , like its counterparts in the rest of the Soviet bloc, did little more than rubber-stamp decisions already made by the MSzMP. \n K\xc3\xa1d\xc3\xa1r retired on 22 May 1988 and was succeeded by Prime Minister K\xc3\xa1roly Gr\xc3\xb3sz . However, Gr\xc3\xb3sz soon found himself eclipsed by a group of radical reformers who favored establishing a market economy. On 28 January 1989, young Politburo member and minister of state Imre Pozsgay announced during an interview with the radio program 168 Hours that the Poliburo`s historical sub-committee regarded the events of 1956 as a \'people\'s uprising\'. This announcement, not approved in advance by the Politburo, provoked and catalyzed various developments within the party, and brought about sudden and ever-escalating changes that led to the ending of Communism in Hungary and the dissolution of the MSzMP. [ 1 ] \n By the summer of 1989, the party\'s radical reformers, led by Prime Minister Miklos Nemeth , Foreign Minister Gyula Horn , Rezs\xc5\x91 Nyers and Pozsgay, had gained control of the party. On 26 June 1989, the Politburo was replaced by a four-man collective presidency chaired by Nyers. Although Gr\xc3\xb3sz remained general secretary, Nyers now outranked him. On 7 October 1989 the MSzMP was dissolved and refounded as the Hungarian Socialist Party , a Western-style social democratic party. A small group of MSzMP members led by Gr\xc3\xb3sz opposed this move, and went on to form the Hungarian Communist Workers\' Party on 17 December 1989. \n \n \n \n \n Contents \n \n \n 1 Leaders of the Hungarian Socialist Workers\' Party \n \n 1.1 General Secretaries \n 1.2 Chairman of the Presidency of the Political Executive Committee \n \n \n 2 See also \n 3 References \n \n \n \n \n [ edit ] Leaders of the Hungarian Socialist Workers\' Party \n [ edit ] General Secretaries \n \n J\xc3\xa1nos K\xc3\xa1d\xc3\xa1r 25 October 1956 \xe2\x80\x93 22 May 1988 \n K\xc3\xa1roly Gr\xc3\xb3sz 22 May 1988 \xe2\x80\x93 26 June 1989 (Continued as general secretary until 7 October 1989 but outranked by Rezs\xc5\x91 Nyers the Chairman of the 4-man Presidency of the newly created Political Executive Committee which replaced the Politburo after 26 June 1989) \n \n [ edit ] Chairman of the Presidency of the Political Executive Committee \n \n Rezs\xc5\x91 Nyers 26 June 1989 \xe2\x80\x93 7 October 1989 \n \n [ edit ] See also \n \n Gyula Horn \n Imre Pozsgay \n List of political parties in Hungary \n Mikl\xc3\xb3s N\xc3\xa9meth \n Politics of Hungary \n \n [ edit ] References \n \n \n ^  http://www.coldwar.hu/html/en/publications/roundtable_kalmar.html \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n v \n t \n e \n \n \n Ruling Communist parties in the Eastern Bloc \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n Eastern Bloc politics \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n &#160;&#160;&#160; \n \n \n \n People\'s Republic of Albania \n \n Party of Labour of Albania \n \n \n \n \n \n \n People\'s Republic of Bulgaria \n \n Bulgarian Communist Party \n \n \n \n \n \n \n Czechoslovak Socialist Republic \n \n Communist Part