e economy so that people who were best suited for particular jobs because of their desires and the skills should be placed in those positions, because it would bring the most benefit to society. example: if you love to cook and are good at it, the government should see to it that you are a cook. \r\nRemember though Marx&#039;s views weren&#039;t totally created by Marx alone. Matter of fact his views may just as well benefit a corporation if it wasn&#039;t for the infuence of Engles and its very critical nature of capitalism. \r\n \r\nGenerally in contrast communism is a decentralization of government power in an attempt to create a stateless classless society but there exists many philosophies of how this may be achieved, which most revolve around some sort of communitarian organization. \r\n \r\nSocialism is centralization of control over production and distribution of goods and services. The soul driving force instead of like in marxist ideals of placing people into society positions that they are suited for, the motivation would be police powers of the government. \r\nThe government dictates what is produced, what will be done with it, and how much will be charged. Even if you are allowed to own a business, if you don&#039;t follow the guidelines you&#039;ll end up getting your bsuiness siezed and thrown in jail. \r\nThink of it as how our government treats drugs. They allow certain types to be produced, and dictates how they will be distributed. They don&#039;t so much as control price other than busting black markets that sell for less or sel drugs that aren&#039;t approved to be produced and sold. \r\n \r\nLibertarianism seeks to decentralize government authority in all aspects of life. I can see where some people could somewhat compare it to the same goals in communism, but realistically they are focusing on two different objectives, since communism seems to retain strict social controls while libertarians are socially liberal. \n\n    \n     4 years ago \n\