and subtly critical work began to be produced. The regime loosened its emphasis on socialist realism; thus, for instance, many protagonists of the novels of author Yury Trifonov concerned themselves with problems of daily life rather than with building socialism. An underground dissident literature, known as samizdat , developed during this late period. In architecture the Khrushchev era mostly focused on functional design as opposed to the highly decorated style of Stalin\'s epoch. \n In the second half of the 1980s, Gorbachev\'s policies of perestroika and glasnost significantly expanded freedom of expression in the media and press. [ 150 ] \n See also \n \n Eurasian Union \n Index of Soviet Union-related articles \n Soviet Empire \n \n \n \n   History&#160;portal  \n   Soviet Union&#160;portal  \n   Communism&#160;portal  \n \n \n References \n \n \n ^  Declaration \xe2\x84\x96 142-\xd0\x9d of the Soviet of the Republics of the Supreme Soviet of the Soviet Union , formally establishing the dissolution of the Soviet Union as a state and subject of international law. (Russian) \n ^  73 Years of State Atheism in the Soviet Union, ended amid collapse in 1990 \n ^  Bridget O\'Laughlin (1975) Marxist Approaches in Anthropology Annual Review of Anthropology Vol. 4: pp. 341\xe2\x80\x9370 (October 1975) doi : 10.1146/annurev.an.04.100175.002013 . \nWilliam Roseberry (1997) Marx and Anthropology Annual Review of Anthropology, Vol. 26: pp. 25\xe2\x80\x9346 (October 1997) doi : 10.1146/annurev.anthro.26.1.25 \n ^  Robert Service (9 September 2005). Stalin: a biography . Picador. ISBN &#160; 978-0-330-41913-0 . &#160; \n ^  Norman Davies: "Since 75%\xe2\x80\x9380% of all German losses were inflicted on the eastern front it follows that the efforts of the Western allies accounted for only 20%\xe2\x80\x9325%". Source: Sunday Times, 05/11/2006. \n ^  Mr. David Holloway (27 March 1996). Stalin and the Bomb . Yale University Press. p.&#160;18. ISBN &#160; 978-0-300-06664-7 . &#160